# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: renewable-integration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] "Ancillary services are all services required by the transmission or distribution system operator to enable them to maintain the integrity and stability of the transmission or distribution system as well as the power quality".
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Ancillary services are specialty services and functions provided by actors within the electric grid that facilitate and support the continuous flow of electricity, so that the demand for electrical energy is met in real time.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] The term ancillary services is used to refer to a variety of operations beyond generation and transmission that are required to maintain grid stability and security.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] These services generally include active power control or frequency control and reactive power control or voltage control, on various timescales.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Traditionally, ancillary services have been provided by large production units such as synchronous generators.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] With the integration of more intermittent generation and the development of smart grid technologies, the provision of ancillary services is extended to smaller distributed generation and consumption units.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Electricity frequency is directly connected to the balance of consumption and generation of active power ( $\Delta P=P_{generation}-P_{consume}$ ) and the total rotating energy ( $W_{tot,kin}$ ) of the synchronous power system.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Where S is the total exchange of active power for the entire grid and H is the normalized inertia constant for the system.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] A system with a small amount of total rotating kinetic energy will be more sensitive to deviations in $\Delta P$ , as the frequency's derivative will be more significantly affected.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] As the total inertia of synchronous grids decreases due to the increasing integration of renewable generation sources, the methodologies and requirements for enabling converter-based generation units to control grid frequency with greater speed and precision are becoming more important.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Frequency control refers to the need to ensure that the grid frequency stays within a specific range of the nominal frequency.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Mismatch between electricity generation and demand causes variations in frequency, so control services are required to bring the frequency back to its nominal value and ensure it does not vary out of range.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] where Pm is the change in power of the system.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] If we have multiple generators, each might have its own R.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] This simple equation can be rearranged to find the change in power that corresponds to a given change in frequency.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Consumer loads expect voltage within a certain range, and the regulators require it be within a certain percent of the nominal voltage (for example, in the US it is ±5%).
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Reactive power can be used to compensate the voltage drops, but must be provided closer to the loads than real power needs (this is because reactive power tend to travel badly through the grid).
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Notice that voltage can be controlled also using transformer taps and voltage regulators.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Scheduling and dispatch are necessary because in most electrical systems energy storage is nearly zero, so at any instant, the power into the system (produced by a generator) must equal the power out of the system (demand from consumers).
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Since production must so closely match demand, careful scheduling and dispatch are necessary.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Usually performed by the independent system operator or transmission system operator, both are services dedicated to the commitment and coordination of the generation and transmission units in order to maintain the reliability of the power grid.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Scheduling refers to before-the-fact actions (like scheduling a generator to produce a certain amount of power the next week), while dispatch refers to the real-time control of the available resources.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Since production and demand must match so perfectly (see Scheduling and dispatch), operating reserves help make up the difference when production is too low.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] An operating reserve is a generator that can quickly be dispatched to ensure that there is sufficient energy generation to meet load.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Spinning reserves are generators that are already online and can rapidly increase their power output to meet fast changes in demand.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Spinning reserves are required because demand can vary on short timescales and rapid response is needed.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Other operating reserves are generators that can be dispatched by the operator to meet demand, but that cannot respond as quickly as spinning reserves, and grid battery storage that can respond within tens of milliseconds, generally faster than even spinning reserve.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] The grid integration of renewable generation simultaneously requires additional ancillary services and has the potential to provide ancillary services to the grid.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] The inverters that are installed with distributed generation systems and roof top solar systems have the potential to provide many of the ancillary services that are traditionally provided by spinning generators and voltage regulators.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] These services include reactive power compensation, voltage regulation, flicker control, active power filtering and harmonic cancellation.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Wind turbines with variable-speed generators have the potential to add synthetic inertia to the grid and assist in frequency control.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] CAISO tested the 131 MW Tule wind farm's synchronverter in 2018, and found it could perform some of the grid services similar or better than traditional generators.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Hydro-Québec began requiring synthetic inertia in 2005 as the first grid operator, demanding a temporary 6% power boost when countering frequency drop by combining the power electronics with the rotational inertia of a wind turbine rotor.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Similar requirements came into effect in Europe in 2016.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Plug-in electric vehicles have the potential to be utilized to provide ancillary services to the grid, specifically load regulation and spinning reserves.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Plug-in electric vehicles can behave like distributed energy storage and have the potential to discharge power back to the grid through bidirectional flow, referred to as vehicle-to-grid (V2G).
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] Plug-in electric vehicles have the ability to supply power at a fast rate which enables them to be used like spinning reserves and provide grid stability with the increased use of intermittent generation such as wind and solar.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] According to the study cited in the reference, which compared the profitability of offering operating reserve ancillary service with the sales of V2G energy from a fleet of vehicles, providing operating reserve regulation service is more profitable than selling V2G energy alone.
[src:renewable-integration/ancillary-services-electric-power] However, the technologies to utilize electric vehicles to provide ancillary services are not yet widely implemented, but there is much anticipation of their potential.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] In the electric power industry, **curtailment** is an involuntary reduction of the electric generator output ("**dispatch down**") made to maintain grid stability (for example, in grid balancing).
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] While curtailment is a standard technique that has been applied throughout the history of electric power production, in the 21st century it has become an economic issue for the owners of wind and solar generation plants.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] These variable renewable energy plants, due to the absence of an expendable resource (like fuel), have quite low marginal electricity production costs, so curtailment affects the economics of projects in a much more significant way than with conventional units.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] Curtailment is a loss of potentially useful energy and may impact power purchase agreements.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] However, using all available energy may require costly methods such as building new power lines or storage, becoming more expensive than letting surplus power go unused.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] After ERCOT built a new transmission line from the Competitive Renewable Energy Zone in West Texas to the central cities in the Texas Interconnection in 2013, curtailment was reduced from 8-16% to near zero.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] Curtailment of wind power in western China was around 20% in 2018.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] In 2018, curtailment in the California grid was 460 GWh, or 0.2% of generation.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] Monthly curtailment has since increased to 150-300 GWh in 2020 and 2021 and to 500-700 GWh by 2024/2025, mainly in spring, although 11 GW of batteries also time-shifted some of the surplus power.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] Curtailments mainly happen for solar power at noon as part of the duck curve.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] In Hawaii, curtailment reached 20% on the island of Maui in Hawaii in the second and third quarters of 2020.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] In Ireland, 1.2 TWh of wind power was curtailed in 2022.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] In United Kingdom, 1.35 TWh of wind power was curtailed in early 2023.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] In Australia, 4.5 TWh of solar and wind power was curtailed in 2024.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] In the 2 years from October 2022 to September 2024, 2.9% of solar power in Spain was curtailed.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] Greece curtailed 0.9 TWh in 2024, and 2 TWh of green power in 2025.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] In 2025 in the Cyprus grid, almost half of distributed large scale solar power was curtailed.
[src:renewable-integration/curtailment-electricity] Curtailment can be reduced or avoided completely through transmission upgrades, demand response, increased energy storage, and better energy forecasting (including forecasting for price, wind and solar).
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] The **duck curve** is a graph showing the electricity demand remaining after subtracting electricity supplied by variable renewable energy sources (primarily solar) over the course of a day.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] This highlights the timing imbalance between demand and solar power generation, which must be filled by dispatchable generation (usually non-renewable).
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] The curve is named for its visual similarity to the outline of a duck.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] Used in utility-scale electricity generation, the term was coined in 2012 by the California Independent System Operator.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] In some energy markets, daily peak demand occurs after sunset, when solar power is no longer available.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] In Hawaii, significant adoption of solar generation has led to the more pronounced curve known as the Nessie curve.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] Without any form of energy storage, after times of high solar generation, power companies must rapidly increase other forms of power generation around the time of sunset to compensate for the loss of solar generation, a major concern for grid operators where there is rapid growth of photovoltaics.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] Storage such as dammed hydropower can fix these issues if it can be implemented.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] Short term use batteries, at a large enough scale of use, can help to flatten the duck curve and prevent generator use fluctuation and can help to maintain voltage profile.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] A major challenge is deploying mitigating capacity at a rate that keeps up with the growth of solar energy production.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] The effects of the duck curve have happened faster than anticipated.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] The California Independent System Operator (CAISO) has been monitoring and analyzing the Duck Curve and its future expectations for about a half a century now and their biggest finding is the growing gap between morning and evening hours prices relative to midday hours prices.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] Energy Information Administration, found that the wholesale energy market prices over the past six months during the 5 pm to 8 pm period (the "neck" of the duck) have increased to $60 per megawatt-hour, compared to about $35 per megawatt-hour in the same time frame in 2016.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] However, on the other side they have measured a drastic decrease in the midday prices, nearing $15 per megawatt-hour.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] These high peaks and deep valleys are only showing continued trends of going further apart making this Duck Curve even more prevalent as renewable energy production continues to grow.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] A crucial part of this curve comes from the **net load** ("the difference between expected load and anticipated electricity production from the range of renewable energy sources").
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] During the midday, large amounts of solar energy are created, which partially contributes to lower demand for additional electricity.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] Increasing battery storage can mitigate the issues of solar abundance during the day.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] When excess solar energy is stored during the day and used in the evening, the price disparity between inexpensive midday and expensive evening energy can be reduced.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] Enough total solar technology exists to power the world, but there is a current lack of infrastructure to store solar energy for later use.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] An oversupply of energy during low demand coupled with a lack of supply during high demand explains the large disparity between midday and evening energy prices.
[src:renewable-integration/duck-curve] As of 2022, up to 6 GWh is shifted per day from low price to high price periods.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] As of the beginning of 2020s, the actual balancing service was provided primarily by the conventional power stations: frequently, the only quick-response safety margin is the inertial response provided by the kinetic energy of the physically rotating machinery (synchronous generators and turbines).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] If there is a mismatch between supply and demand the generators absorb extra energy by speeding up or produce more power by slowing down causing the utility frequency (either 50 or 60 hertz) to increase or decrease.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] However, the frequency cannot deviate too much from the target: many units of the electrical equipment can be destroyed by the out-of-bounds frequency and thus will automatically disconnect from the grid to protect themselves, potentially triggering a blackout.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] Since the 20th century grid balancing has become less predictable with more variable renewable energy being installed into the grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] This has resulted in wind farms being turned off at night time, when wind is high and demand for power is low.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] In Scotland this has resulted in payouts, most recently over £6m in 33 days has been paid by the grid to wind farms to not generate electricity.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] Constraint payments are made to other electricity suppliers as well as wind.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] In 2011/2012, payments by the National Grid in the UK totaled £324 million of which £31 million went to wind.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] In 2012/2013, thanks to improved transmission capability, they were £130 million of which only £7 million were for wind.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] This temporary excess of electric energy could alternatively be used in electrolysis of water to make high purity hydrogen fuel used in fuel cells.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-balancing] In areas with little hydroelectricity, pumped storage systems such as the Dinorwig Power Station can allow the energy to be used for operational reserve or at times of peak demand rather than run a natural gas peaking power plant.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] An **electrical grid** (or **electricity network**) is an interconnected network for electricity delivery from producers to consumers.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electrical grids consist of power stations, electrical substations to step voltage up or down, electric power transmission to carry power over long distances, and finally electric power distribution to customers.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In that last step, voltage is stepped down again to the required service voltage.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Power stations are typically built close to energy sources and far from densely populated areas.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electrical grids vary in size and can cover whole countries or continents.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] From small to large there are microgrids, wide area synchronous grids, and super grids.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The combined transmission and distribution network is part of electricity delivery, known as the *power grid*.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Grids are nearly always synchronous, meaning all distribution areas operate with three phase alternating current (AC) frequencies synchronized (so that voltage swings occur at almost the same time).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] This allows transmission of AC power throughout the area, connecting the electricity generators with consumers.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Grids can enable more efficient electricity markets.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Although electrical grids are widespread, as of 2016, 1.4 billion people worldwide were not connected to an electricity grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] As electrification increases, the number of people with access to grid electricity is growing.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] About 840 million people (mostly in Africa), which is ca.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] 11% of the World's population, had no access to grid electricity in 2017, down from 1.2 billion in 2010.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electrical grids can be prone to malicious intrusion or attack; thus, there is a need for electric grid security.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Also as electric grids modernize and introduce computer technology, cyber threats start to become a security risk.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Particular concerns relate to the more complex computer systems needed to manage grids.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A microgrid is a local grid that is usually part of the regional wide-area synchronous grid, but which can disconnect and operate autonomously.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] It might do this in times when the main grid is affected by outages.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] This is known as islanding, and it might run indefinitely on its own resources.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Compared to larger grids, microgrids typically use a lower voltage distribution network and distributed generators.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Microgrids may not only be more resilient, but may be cheaper to implement in isolated areas.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A design goal is that a local area produces all of the energy it uses.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A *wide area synchronous grid* (also called an "interconnection" in North America) is an electrical grid at a regional scale or greater that operates at a synchronized frequency and is electrically tied together during normal system conditions.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] For example, there are four major interconnections in North America (the Western Interconnection, the Eastern Interconnection, the Quebec Interconnection and the Texas Interconnection).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In Europe, one large grid connects most of Western Europe.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] These are also known as synchronous zones, the largest of which is the synchronous grid of Continental Europe (ENTSO-E) with 667 gigawatts (GW) of generation, and the widest region served being that of the IPS/UPS system serving countries of the former Soviet Union.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Synchronous grids with ample capacity facilitate electricity market trading across wide areas.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In the ENTSO-E in 2008, over 350,000 megawatt hours were sold per day on the European Energy Exchange (EEX).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Each of the interconnects in North America are run at a nominal 60 Hz, while those of Europe run at 50 Hz.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] One disadvantage of a wide-area synchronous grid is that problems in one part can have repercussions across the whole grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] For example, in 2018, Kosovo used more power than it generated due to a dispute with Serbia, leading to the phase across the whole synchronous grid of Continental Europe lagging behind what it should have been.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] This caused certain kinds of clocks to become six minutes slow.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A *super grid* or *supergrid* is a wide-area transmission network that is intended to make possible the trade of high volumes of electricity across great distances.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] It is sometimes also referred to as a *mega grid*.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Super grids can support a global energy transition by smoothing local fluctuations of wind energy and solar energy.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In this context, they are considered as a key technology to mitigate global warming.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Super grids typically use high-voltage direct current (HVDC) to transmit electricity long distances.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The latest generation of HVDC power lines can transmit energy with losses of only 1.6% per 1000 km.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electric utilities between regions are many times interconnected for improved economy and reliability.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electrical interconnectors allow for economies of scale, allowing energy to be purchased from large, efficient sources.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Utilities can draw power from generator reserves from a different region to ensure continuing, reliable power and diversify their loads.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Interconnection also allows regions to have access to cheap bulk energy by receiving power from different sources.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] For example, one region may be producing cheap hydro power during high water seasons, but in low water seasons, another area may be producing cheaper power through wind, allowing both regions to access cheaper energy sources from one another during different times of the year.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Neighboring utilities also help others to maintain the overall system frequency and also help manage tie transfers between utility regions.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electricity Interconnection Level (EIL) of a grid is the ratio of the total interconnector power to the grid divided by the installed production capacity of the grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Within the EU, it has set a target of national grids reaching 10% by 2020, and 15% by 2030.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electricity generation is the process of generating electric power at power stations.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] This is done ultimately from sources of primary energy typically with electromechanical generators driven by heat engines from fossil, nuclear, and geothermal sources, or driven by the kinetic energy of water or wind.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Other power sources are photovoltaics driven by solar insolation, and grid batteries.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The sum of the power outputs of generators on the grid is the production of the grid, typically measured in gigawatts (GW).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electric power transmission is the bulk movement of electrical energy from a generating site, via a web of interconnected lines, to an electrical substation, from which is connected to the distribution system.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] This networked system of connections is distinct from the local wiring between high-voltage substations and customers.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Transmission networks are built with redundant pathways to prevent a single point of failure.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In case of line failures this redundancy allows power to be simply rerouted while repairs are done.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Because the power is often generated far from where it is consumed, the transmission system can cover great distances.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] For a given amount of power, transmission efficiency is greater at higher voltages and lower currents.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Therefore, voltages are stepped up at the generating station, and stepped down at local substations for distribution to customers.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Three-phase, compared to single-phase, can deliver much more power for a given amount of wire, since the neutral and ground wires are shared.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Further, three-phase generators and motors are more efficient than their single-phase counterparts.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] However, for conventional conductors one of the main losses are resistive losses which are a square law on current, and depend on distance.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] High voltage AC transmission lines can lose 1–4% per hundred miles.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] However, high-voltage direct current can have half the losses of AC.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Over very long distances, these efficiencies can offset the additional cost of the required AC/DC converter stations at each end.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Substations may perform many different functions but usually transform voltage from low to high (step up) and from high to low (step down).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Between the generator and the final consumer, the voltage may be transformed several times.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Distribution is the final stage in the delivery of power; it carries electricity from the transmission system to individual consumers.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Substations connect to the transmission system and lower the transmission voltage to medium voltage ranging between 2 kV and 35 kV.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] But the voltage levels varies very much between different countries, in Sweden medium voltage are normally 10 kV between 20 kV.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Primary distribution lines carry this medium voltage power to distribution transformers located near the customer's premises.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Distribution transformers again lower the voltage to the utilization voltage.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Customers demanding a much larger amount of power may be connected directly to the primary distribution level or the subtransmission level.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Distribution networks are divided into two types, radial or network.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In cities and towns of North America, the grid tends to follow the classic *radially fed* design.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A substation receives its power from the transmission network, the power is stepped down with a transformer and sent to a bus from which feeders fan out in all directions across the countryside.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] These feeders carry three-phase power, and tend to follow the major streets near the substation.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] As the distance from the substation grows, the fanout continues as smaller laterals spread out to cover areas missed by the feeders.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] This tree-like structure grows outward from the substation, but for reliability reasons, usually contains at least one unused backup connection to a nearby substation.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] This connection can be enabled in case of an emergency, so that a portion of a substation's service territory can be alternatively fed by another substation.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] As of 2020, the largest form of grid energy storage is dammed hydroelectricity, with both conventional hydroelectric generation as well as pumped storage hydroelectricity.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Developments in battery storage have enabled commercially viable projects to store energy during peak production and release during peak demand, and for use when production unexpectedly falls giving time for slower responding resources to be brought online.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Two alternatives to grid storage are the use of peaking power plants to fill in supply gaps and demand response to shift load to other times.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The demand, or load on an electrical grid is the total electrical power being removed by the users of the grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The graph of the demand over time is called the *demand curve*.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Baseload is the minimum load on the grid over any given period, peak demand is the maximum load.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Historically, baseload was commonly met by equipment that was relatively cheap to run, that ran continuously for weeks or months at a time, but globally this is becoming less common.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The extra peak demand requirements are sometimes produced by expensive peaking plants that are generators optimised to come on-line quickly but these too are becoming less common.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] However, if the demand of electricity exceeds the capacity of a local power grid, it will cause safety issues like burning out.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Grids are designed to supply electricity to their customers at largely constant voltages.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] This has to be achieved with varying demand, variable reactive loads, and even nonlinear loads, with electricity provided by generators and distribution and transmission equipment that are not perfectly reliable.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Often grids use tap changers on transformers near to the consumers to adjust the voltage and keep it within specification.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In a synchronous grid all the generators must run at the same frequency, and must stay very nearly in phase with each other and the grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Generation and consumption must be balanced across the entire grid, because energy is consumed as it is produced.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] For rotating generators, a local governor regulates the driving torque, maintaining almost constant rotation speed as loading changes.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Energy is stored in the immediate short term by the rotational kinetic energy of the generators.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Although the speed is kept largely constant, small deviations from the nominal system frequency are very important in regulating individual generators and are used as a way of assessing the equilibrium of the grid as a whole.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] When the grid is lightly loaded the grid frequency runs above the nominal frequency, and this is taken as an indication by Automatic generation control (AGC) systems across the network that generators should reduce their output.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Conversely, when the grid is heavily loaded, the frequency naturally slows, and governors adjust their generators so that more power is output (droop speed control).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] When generators have identical droop speed control settings it ensures that multiple parallel generators with the same settings share load in proportion to their rating.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In addition, there's often central control, which can change the parameters of the AGC systems over timescales of a minute or longer to further adjust the regional network flows and the operating frequency of the grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] For timekeeping purposes, the nominal frequency will be allowed to vary in the short term, but is adjusted to prevent line-operated clocks from gaining or losing significant time over the course of a whole 24 hour period.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Neighbouring grids that are not directly connected are almost always out-of-phase with each other.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Instead, high-voltage direct current lines or variable-frequency transformers are used, which allow two out-of-phase synchronous grids to share power.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The sum of the maximum power outputs (nameplate capacity) of the generators attached to an electrical grid might be considered to be the capacity of the grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] However, in practice, they are never run flat out simultaneously.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Typically, some generators are kept running at lower output powers (spinning reserve) to deal with failures as well as variation in demand.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In addition generators can be off-line for maintenance or other reasons, such as availability of energy inputs (fuel, water, wind, sun etc.) or pollution constraints.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Most grid codes specify that the load is shared between the generators in merit order according to their marginal cost (i.e. cheapest first) and sometimes their environmental impact.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Thus cheap electricity providers tend to be run flat out almost all the time, and the more expensive producers are only run when necessary.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A central authority is usually designated to facilitate communication and develop protocols to maintain a stable grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] For example, the North American Electric Reliability Corporation gained binding powers in the United States in 2006, and has advisory powers in the applicable parts of Canada and Mexico.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The U.S. government has also designated National Interest Electric Transmission Corridors, where it believes transmission bottlenecks have developed.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Where multiple utilities own generators connected to one electrical grid power pools are often formed which have agreements about responsibilities.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Each grid may have a system operator that is responsible for day-to-day running of one or more grids.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Failures are usually associated with generators or power transmission lines tripping circuit breakers due to faults leading to a loss of generation capacity for customers, or excess demand.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] This will often cause the frequency to reduce, and the remaining generators will react and together attempt to stabilize above the minimum.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] If that is not possible then a number of scenarios can occur.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A large failure in one part of the grid—unless quickly compensated for—can cause current to re-route itself to flow from the remaining generators to consumers over transmission lines of insufficient capacity, causing further failures.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] One downside to a widely connected grid is thus the possibility of cascading failure and widespread power outage.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A *brownout* is an intentional or unintentional drop in voltage in an electrical power supply system.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Intentional brownouts are used for load reduction in an emergency.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The reduction lasts for minutes or hours, as opposed to short-term voltage sag (or dip).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The term brownout comes from the dimming experienced by incandescent lighting when the voltage sags.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A voltage reduction may be an effect of disruption of an electrical grid, or may occasionally be imposed in an effort to reduce load and prevent a power outage, known as a blackout.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A *power outage* (also called a *power cut*, a *power out*, a *power blackout*, *power failure* or a *blackout*) is a loss of the electric power to a particular area.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Power failures can be caused by faults at power stations, damage to electric transmission lines, substations or other parts of the distribution system, a short circuit, cascading failure, fuse or circuit breaker operation, and human error.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Power failures are particularly critical at sites where the environment and public safety are at risk.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Institutions such as hospitals, sewage treatment plants, mines, shelters and the like will usually have backup power sources such as standby generators, which will automatically start up when electrical power is lost.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Other critical systems, such as telecommunication, are also required to have emergency power.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The battery room of a telephone exchange usually has arrays of lead–acid batteries for backup and also a socket for connecting a generator during extended periods of outage.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electrical generation and transmission systems may not always meet peak demand requirements— the greatest amount of electricity required by all utility customers within a given region.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In these situations, overall demand must be lowered, either by turning off service to some devices or cutting back the supply voltage (brownouts), in order to prevent uncontrolled service disruptions such as power outages (widespread blackouts) or equipment damage.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Utilities may impose load shedding on service areas via targeted blackouts, rolling blackouts or by agreements with specific high-use industrial consumers to turn off equipment at times of system-wide peak demand.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A *black start* is the process of restoring an electric power station or a part of an electric grid to operation without relying on the external electric power transmission network to recover from a total or partial shutdown.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Normally, the electric power used within the plant is provided from the station's own generators.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] If all of the plant's main generators are shut down, station service power is provided by drawing power from the grid through the plant's transmission line.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] However, during a wide-area outage, off-site power from the grid is not available.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In the absence of grid power, a so-called black start needs to be performed to bootstrap the power grid into operation.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] To provide a black start, some power stations have small diesel generators, normally called the *black start diesel generator* (BSDG), which can be used to start larger generators (of several megawatts capacity), which in turn can be used to start the main power station generators.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Generating plants using steam turbines require station service power of up to 10% of their capacity for boiler feedwater pumps, boiler forced-draft combustion air blowers, and for fuel preparation.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] It is uneconomical to provide such a large standby capacity at each station, so black-start power must be provided over designated tie lines from another station.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Often hydroelectric power plants are designated as the black-start sources to restore network interconnections.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] A hydroelectric station needs very little initial power to start (just enough to open the intake gates and provide excitation current to the generator field coils), and can put a large block of power on line very quickly to allow start-up of fossil-fuel or nuclear stations.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Certain types of combustion turbine can be configured for black start, providing another option in places without suitable hydroelectric plants.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In 2017 a utility in Southern California has successfully demonstrated the use of a battery energy storage system to provide a black start, firing up a combined cycle gas turbine from an idle state.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Despite novel institutional arrangements and network designs, power delivery infrastructures is experiencing aging across the developed world.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Demand response is a grid management technique where retail or wholesale customers are requested or incentivised either electronically or manually to reduce their load.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Currently, transmission grid operators use demand response to request load reduction from major energy users such as industrial plants.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Technologies such as smart metering can encourage customers to use power when electricity is plentiful by allowing for variable pricing.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The smart grid is an enhancement of the 20th century electrical grid, using two-way communications and distributed so-called intelligent devices.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Two-way flows of electricity and information could improve the delivery network.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Research is mainly focused on three systems of a smart grid – the infrastructure system, the management system, and the protection system.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electronic power conditioning and control of the production and distribution of electricity are important aspects of the smart grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The smart grid represents the full suite of current and proposed responses to the challenges of electricity supply.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Numerous contributions to the overall improvement of energy infrastructure efficiency are anticipated from the deployment of smart grid technology, in particular including demand-side management.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The improved flexibility of the smart grid permits greater penetration of highly variable renewable energy sources such as solar power and wind power, even without the addition of energy storage.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Smart grids could also monitor/control residential devices that are noncritical during periods of peak power consumption, and return their function during nonpeak hours.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Concerns with smart grid technology mostly focus on smart meters, items enabled by them, and general security issues.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Roll-out of smart grid technology also implies a fundamental re-engineering of the electricity services industry, although typical usage of the term is focused on the technical infrastructure.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Smart grid policy is organized in Europe as Smart Grid European Technology Platform.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Policy in the United States is described in Title 42 of the United States Code.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Smart grids are not to be confused with sector coupled smart energy systems, as smart grids primarily refers to the power sector, while smart energy system use an integrated holistic focus which also includes other sectors of the energy system with the intent to create synergies between them.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Resistance to distributed generation among grid operators may encourage providers to leave the grid and instead distribute power to smaller geographies.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The Rocky Mountain Institute and other studies foresee widescale grid defection.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] However, grid defection may be less likely in places such as Germany that have greater power demands in the winter.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Early electric energy was produced near the device or service requiring that energy.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In the 1880s, electricity competed with steam, hydraulics, and especially coal gas.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Coal gas was first produced on customer's premises but later evolved into gasification plants that enjoyed economies of scale.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In the industrialized world, cities had networks of piped gas, used for lighting.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] But gas lamps produced poor light, wasted heat, made rooms hot and smoky, and gave off hydrogen and carbon monoxide.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In the 1880s electric lighting soon became advantageous compared to gas lighting.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Electric utility companies established central stations to take advantage of economies of scale and moved to centralized power generation, distribution, and system management.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] After the war of the currents was settled in favor of AC power, with long-distance power transmission it became possible to interconnect stations to balance the loads and improve load factors.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Historically, transmission and distribution lines were owned by the same company, but starting in the 1990s, many countries have liberalized the regulation of the electricity market in ways that have led to the separation of the electricity transmission business from the distribution business.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In the United Kingdom, Charles Merz, of the Merz & McLellan consulting partnership, built the Neptune Bank Power Station near Newcastle upon Tyne in 1901, and by 1912 had developed into the largest integrated power system in Europe.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Merz was appointed head of a parliamentary committee and his findings led to the Williamson Report of 1918, which in turn created the Electricity (Supply) Act 1919.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The bill was the first step towards an integrated electricity system.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In 1925 the Weir Committee recommended the creation of a "national gridiron" and so the Electricity (Supply) Act 1926 created the Central Electricity Board (CEB).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The CEB standardized the nation's electricity supply and established the first synchronized AC grid, running at 132 kilovolts and 50 hertz but initially operated as regional grids.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] After brief overnight interconnection in 1937 they permanently and officially joined in 1938 becoming the UK National Grid.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In France, electrification began in the 1900s, with 700 communes in 1919, and 36,528 in 1938.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] At the same time, these close networks began to interconnect: Paris in 1907 at 12 kV, the Pyrénées in 1923 at 150 kV, and finally almost all of the country interconnected by 1938 at 220 kV.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In 1946, the grid was the world's most dense.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] That year the state nationalised the industry, by uniting the private companies as Électricité de France.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The frequency was standardised at 50 Hz, and the 225 kV network replaced 110 kV and 120 kV.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Since 1956, service voltage has been standardised at 220/380 V, replacing the previous 127/220 V.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] During the 1970s, the 400 kV network, the new European standard, was implemented.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Starting on May 29, 1986, the end user service voltage will progressively change to 230/400 V ±10%.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In the United States in the 1920s, utilities formed joint-operations to share peak load coverage and backup power.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In 1934, with the passage of the Public Utility Holding Company Act (U.S.), electric utilities were recognized as public goods of importance and were given outlined restrictions and regulatory oversight of their operations.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The Energy Policy Act of 1992 required transmission line owners to allow electric generation companies open access to their network and led to a restructuring of how the electric industry operated in an effort to create competition in power generation.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] No longer were electric utilities built as vertical monopolies, where generation, transmission and distribution were handled by a single company.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] Now, the three stages could be split among various companies, in an effort to provide fair access to high voltage transmission.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] The Energy Policy Act of 2005 allowed incentives and loan guarantees for alternative energy production and advance innovative technologies that avoided greenhouse emissions.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In China, electrification began in the 1950s.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In August 1961, the electrification of the Baoji-Fengzhou section of the Baocheng Railway was completed and delivered for operation, becoming China's first electrified railway.
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] From 1958 to 1998, China's electrified railway reached 6,200 miles (10,000 kilometres).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] As of the end of 2017, this number has reached 54,000 miles (87,000 kilometres).
[src:renewable-integration/grid-connection] In the current railway electrification system of China, State Grid Corporation of China—Archived 2021-12-21 at the Wayback Machine—is an important power supplier.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] The use of small amounts of intermittent power has little effect on grid operations.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] Using larger amounts of intermittent power may require upgrades or even a redesign of the grid infrastructure.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] More connections between the energy sector and the building, transport and industrial sectors may also help.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] The penetration of intermittent renewables in most power grids is low: global electricity generation in 2021 was 7% wind and 4% solar.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] However, in 2021 Denmark, Luxembourg and Uruguay generated over 40% of their electricity from wind and solar.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] Characteristics of variable renewables include their unpredictability, variability, and low operating costs.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] These, along with renewables typically being asynchronous generators, provide a challenge to grid operators, who must make sure supply and demand are matched.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] Solutions include energy storage, demand response, availability of overcapacity and sector coupling.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] Smaller isolated grids may be less tolerant to high levels of penetration.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] Matching power demand to supply is not a problem specific to intermittent power sources.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] Existing power grids already contain elements of uncertainty including sudden and large changes in demand and unforeseen power plant failures.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] Though power grids are already designed to have some capacity in excess of projected peak demand to deal with these problems, significant upgrades may be required to accommodate large amounts of intermittent power.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] Several key terms are useful for understanding the issue of intermittent power sources.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] These terms are not standardized, and variations may be used.
[src:renewable-integration/variable-renewable-energy] Most of these terms also apply to traditional power plants.
